snippet.textDisplay: Wow. I’m in tears. I am so sorry for your loss Laura, and to Ian and all the Love Island family. I can’t imagine how it feels for you as Caroline’s friend and family, I’m absolutely devastated and I only knew her from TV. It is heartbreaking that such a beautiful, vivacious, charming, talented, relatable young woman like Caroline felt she had no other option but end her own life due to the constant scrutiny, trolling, judgment, intrusion and lies from the media, tabloids and trolls. Even if she didn’t already suffer with depression or anxiety or any other mental health issues, this pressure is enough to break anyone. But Caroline did publicly address mental health issues and her own struggles and still these people kept kicking her while she was down. Shame on you. This has to stop. This should not have happened. There has got to be consequences, legislation and justice put in place, in Caroline’s honor, so this does not happen to another vulnerable, honest human being who has chosen to be a public figure or share their story on social media. To Caroline, I hope to God you are at peace and know just how much you are loved and how much we miss you 😘
snippet.textOriginal: Wow. I’m in tears. I am so sorry for your loss Laura, and to Ian and all the Love Island family. I can’t imagine how it feels for you as Caroline’s friend and family, I’m absolutely devastated and I only knew her from TV. It is heartbreaking that such a beautiful, vivacious, charming, talented, relatable young woman like Caroline felt she had no other option but end her own life due to the constant scrutiny, trolling, judgment, intrusion and lies from the media, tabloids and trolls. Even if she didn’t already suffer with depression or anxiety or any other mental health issues, this pressure is enough to break anyone. But Caroline did publicly address mental health issues and her own struggles and still these people kept kicking her while she was down. Shame on you. This has to stop. This should not have happened. There has got to be consequences, legislation and justice put in place, in Caroline’s honor, so this does not happen to another vulnerable, honest human being who has chosen to be a public figure or share their story on social media. To Caroline, I hope to God you are at peace and know just how much you are loved and how much we miss you 😘

snippet.textDisplay: I don’t believe the whole trolls narrative. I think Caroline flack had a lot of showbiz associates like this women here but I don’t think she had any real friends and I don’t think the whole “be kind” thing is very helpful at all. It seems like people like this women are pushing that to further their own careers. Again I don’t think she had any real friends. Suicide is a complicated issue and can’t be fixed with a simple catchphrase or hashtag. We need to start being realistic and honest about these things. It can be tempting to become hysterical and play the blame game but it helps nobody at the end of day. Things are complex.

snippet.textDisplay: My heart goes out to Caroline's family and friends,this is absolutely tragic,heart breaking news that such a beautiful young successful woman chose to take her own life that she was amazing in,it's horrible that celebrities have to face all the issues with the media in the public eye,and made to feel so bad they take their life. These people,are normal people,who make mistakes because we're human,these people are normal human beings just like ourselves that maybe make a wrong choice,take a wrong path,drink a little too much alcohol,stay out too late,argue and fight with their loved ones,just like the rest of us normal human beings out of the public eye,that do all of these normal things in everyday life. They still have feelings and emotions and tempers,behaviours all difficult to control just like any human being.everyone reacts and acts different in different situations etc,everyone does things in haste and regret,we are not programmed to be any different in the public eye to out of the public eye. They are no worse than any other person in simular circumstances,it does not make them a bad person because they have dealt with a situation in the same way many human beings do. It's disgusting that they need to be removed from the public eye,either by themselves or not,we don't lose our jobs if we fight with our loved ones,why should they be made to feel ashamed of anything they do that may be a normal human error/action. Leave them alone for God's sake,we mess up,we do wrong,that's life.it's awful, dreadful disgusting and poor Caroline felt so bad she took her life for this,it breaks my heart,sincerely breaks my heart. What an absolute waste of a beautiful beautiful life,and for what ? Nothing...people who look at stars on our tv screens who judge and bad mouth them for making a normal everyday mistake, well you should be ashamed of yourselves,this is having a massive effect on so many people's lives, it has got to stop. Leave them alone. They mess up. SO WHAT.. my thoughts are with Caroline's family and friends at this dreadful and devastating time. Unbelievably shocking and extremely upsetting.it's so so sad. 😭

snippet.textDisplay: God forbid you survive a suicide attempt though. People are even crueler afterwards. They'll call you selfish and a coward. If you haven't guessed I'm speaking from personal experience. Suicide doesn't make anything better, particularly if you're unfortunate enough to survive, (again in my personal experience) life gets much worse and as ever there is absolutely zero guarantee of it ever improving. People don't know how to handle someone in that kind of pain and so "Friends" melt away like the snow in spring, leaving you more alone than before. Expect a stint in your local nut house, because if having your freedom taken away isn't an incentive to learn to pretend you're fine, I don't know what is. I'm a shadow of the man I used to be. I have regretted every day for 3 years that I wasn't successful, yet somehow I'm still here. It helps that I don't allow myself to hope or dream anymore. I literally get through one day at a time, when I can't do that I take it moment by torturous moment. I often tell myself "amor fati, momento mori" like a mantra, and try to embrace the pain, because the truth is pain is life and life is pain, suffering is what defines us, without it we wouldn't even know we're alive. old freddy fred fred said what doesn't kill you makes you stronger, and i suppose in a way,I am, because now i really don't care how much more I suffer or what happens to me. I'm like a cup flowing over. I'm too tired to write anymore so I'll end with the words of the great emil cioran "why kill yourself? By the time you do it's already too late"

snippet.textDisplay:
The Roman Empire was one of the largest and longest-running empires in human history. With a population of about 65 million, it rivaled its counterpart in the East, the Han Dynasty of 60 million people. At its peak, the Roman Empire spanned about 5 million square kilometers (or 1.9 million square miles), close to the landmass of the Han Dynasty.

After Rome's suppression of Christians, however, this powerful empire went downhill. Stricken by three major plagues, the Western Roman Empire ended in 476. The fourth disaster, the Plague of Justinian (541-542) killed another 25-50 million people, further weakening the empire.

Nero's Defamation and Cruelty
The most notorious attack against Christians came from Emperor Nero between 64 and 65 AD. Nero, who became emperor at 54 AD, killed his mother, brother, and two wives. Numerous historians have documented that, in order to renovate and expand Rome, Nero set fire to the city on July 18, in 64 AD and blamed Christians for the arson. “Nobody dared fight the flames. Attempts to do so were prevented by menacing gangs. Torches, too, were openly thrown in, by men crying that they acted under orders,” wrote historian Tacitus in The Annals.

After labeling Christians a cult and a danger to society, Nero mobilized the Roman public to persecute them. As a result, many Christians were killed – torn apart by beasts or burned alive as human torches.

“In their very deaths they were made the subjects of sport: for they were covered with the hides of wild beasts, and worried to death by dogs, or nailed to crosses, or set fire to, and when the day waned, burned to serve for the evening lights,” wrote Tacitus.

Many people who followed Nero and persecuted Christians soon received retribution. A plague broke out the following autumn in Rome, killing some 30,000 people. Three years later, a rebellion against Nero took place. He fled Rome in AD 68 and died, possibly by suicide.
